ONCA BREAST TC - Adjuvant - PRL173
Docetaxel(75) CTX(600); q21d x 4 cycles
Cycle length = 21 days x 4 cycles

Lab Orders		
Lab Parameters To Assess:
ANC greater than 1,500; platelets greater than 100,000; CrCl greater than 9 mL/min; Total Bili less than or equal to 1 times ULN; ALT less than or equal to 1.5 times ULN; Alk Phos less than or equal to 2.5 times ULN

Baseline Labs:
CBC, SCr, Total Bili, ALT, Alk Phos, Hep-B sAg, Hep-B cAb

Labs Before Each Treatment:
CBC, SCr, Total Bili, ALT, Alk Phos

Outpatient Orders
Dexamethasone (DECADRON) 4 mg tab; QTY #10, Refill: 0
Take 2 tablets PO BID for a total of 5 doses. Start in the morning, one day prior to docetaxel.
Filgrastim (NEUPOGEN) 300 mcg/0.5 mL syringe; QTY# 5, Refill: 0
Inject 0.5 mL subcutaneously daily for 5 days. Start on day 3 of cycle.
Filgrastim (NEUPOGEN) 480 mcg/0.8 mL syringe; QTY# 5, Refill: 0
Inject 0.8 mL subcutaneously daily for 5 days. Start on day 3 of cycle. 
Reminder message:
Select only one filgrastim order: Usual dosage is 300 microgram for patients less than 75 Kg and 480 microgram for those 75 Kg and above.

Premedications	
Hydration/Fluids
0.9% saline 500 mL at 20 mL/hr as primary line to keep vein open.

Ancillary
Dexamethasone (DECADRON) 20 mg in 0.9% saline 100 mL IVPB over 15 minutes.  Give 30 minutes before chemotherapy if patient did not take oral dexamethasone from home.

Antiemetics  (Level 4m):   
Ondansetron (ZOFRAN) 8 mg tab.  Give 3 tablets PO 30 minutes before chemotherapy.
Ondansetron (ZOFRAN) 8 mg in 0.9% saline 100 mL IVPB over 15 minutes.  Give 30 minutes before chemotherapy if patient is unable to tolerate oral formulation.

Chemotherapy	
DOCEtaxel (TAXOTERE) 75 mg/M2/dose (= ____ mg) in 0.9% saline 250 mL IVPB over 60 minutes.  Give day 1 of each cycle.
Cyclophosphamide (CYTOXAN) 600 mg/M2/dose (= ____ mg) in 0.9% saline 250 mL IVPB over 30 minutes.  Give day 1 of each cycle.

PRN and HSR (Hypersensitivity Reaction) Medications	
LORazepam (ATIVAN) 0.5 mg tablet.  Give 1 tab PO PRN nausea, vomiting or anxiety.  May repeat one time in 30 minutes and every 4 hours prn thereafter.
LORazepam (ATIVAN) 0.5 mg injection. Inject 0.5 mg IV push PRN nausea, vomiting or anxiety if unable to tolerate oral formulation.  May repeat one time in 30 minutes and every 4 hours prn thereafter.
Acetaminophen (TYLENOL) 325 mg tab.  Take 2 tablets PO every 4 hours if needed for fever (greater than 100.4 F), myalgias, arthralgias or headache.
Hydrocortisone (SOLU-CORTEF) 100 mg.  Give IV push one time, if needed for hypersensitivity reaction due to chemotherapy.
DiphenhydrAMINE (BENADRYL) 50 mg.  Give IV push one time, if needed for hypersensitivity reaction due to chemotherapy.

Nursing Orders	
•	Verify that patient meets the lab parameters for administration.
•	Perform assessment for toxicity and tolerance.
•	Begin 0.9% saline as primary line to keep vein open.
•	If patient has not taken oral pre-medication at home for docetaxel, administer IV medication as ordered.
•	Use non-PVC bags and tubing to administer docetaxel.
•	For first dose of docetaxel, may start at 50 mL/hr for 15 minutes; if blood pressure is stable and patient tolerates, increase to full rate for total dose to infuse in 1 hour, take vital signs at completion of infusion.
•	Infusion related reactions: STOP infusion immediately, and begin primary solution at wide open rate, notify MD, begin monitoring vital signs and administer prn medication for infusion reaction; 30 minutes after symptoms have resolved, restart docetaxel infusion at 50 % of the rate when reaction occurred.
•	Instruct patient on importance of maintaining oral intake of at least 2 liters per day for 72 hours.
•	Instruct patient to contact health care team if not voiding or taking adequate fluids frequently for 72 hours.
•	Flush IV line with minimum of 30 mL of primary solution before and after each chemotherapy drug.
•	Review discharge medications, instructions and future appointments.
